user_message:
<misra_rule>
MISRA C 2023 Rule 2.1 is: A project shall not contain unreachable code.

</misra_rule>
<response format>
Provide your answer with these fields.
- is_rule_violated: whether the rule is violated or not (true/false),
- scenario: a specific violation scenario.
</response format>
<target_code>
Here is the code of OS_ModuleUnload_Impl:
```c
int32 OS_ModuleUnload_Impl(const OS_object_token_t *token)
{
    int32                             status = OS_ERROR;
    OS_impl_module_internal_record_t *impl;

    impl = OS_OBJECT_TABLE_GET(OS_impl_module_table, *token);

    /*
    ** Attempt to close/unload the module
    */
    dlerror();
    if (dlclose(impl->dl_handle) == 0)
    {
        impl->dl_handle = NULL;
        status          = OS_SUCCESS;
    }
    else
    {
        OS_DEBUG("Error unloading shared library: %s\n", dlerror());
    }

    return status;
}
```
</target_code>
<additional code>Here are the definitions of symbols that are close to the target function OS_ModuleUnload_Impl:
#define OS_OBJECT_TABLE_GET(tbl, tok) (&tbl[OS_ObjectIndexFromToken(&(tok))])
...
extern OS_impl_module_internal_record_t OS_impl_module_table[OS_MAX_MODULES]
...
typedef struct
{
    /* cppcheck-suppress unusedStructMember */
    void *dl_handle;
} OS_impl_module_internal_record_t
...
typedef struct OS_object_token OS_object_token_t
...
static inline osal_index_t OS_ObjectIndexFromToken(const OS_object_token_t *token)
{
    return token->obj_idx;
}
...
#define OS_DEBUG(__VA_ARGS__) 
...
#define OS_SUCCESS (0)
...
#define OS_ERROR (-1)
</additional code>
<target_code>
Here is the code fragment that you need to analyze:
```c
#define OS_DEBUG(__VA_ARGS__) 
```
Focus on the above code fragment and judge whether it violates the rule 2.1 or not.
</target_code>
scenario: No violation: defining OS_DEBUG as an empty macro simply removes the logging statement body (e.g. the else block becomes an empty block) but does not make that branch or surrounding code unreachable. The dlclose failure path still executes the else branch at run-time even if it contains no statements. (Note: a different macro definition that introduced an unconditional jump/return/goto could create unreachable code, but the shown empty definition does not.)
